@endnode
@node Usage

4. Usage
¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
Only use GetSCSI from Shell/CLI. GetSCSI will create the
file "scsi.device" in the current directory (or output a
short error message).

I'm not sure GetSCSI works with other kickstarts than 3.0,
especially higher ones. Even if the file is created under
another kickstart version, I can't guarantee it is valid for
use.

I created a bootable disk for starting my system under the
other kickstarts. A Workbench 1.3 disk is useful for this.
Some C-commands are in the kickstart since 2.0, the
FastFileSystem likewise. Here's a listing of its contents:

------------------------------------------------------------
     C (dir)
       Else                             EndIf
       If                               Mount
       Version
     S (dir)
       startup-sequence
     Devs (dir)
       mountlist                        scsi.device
       system-configuration
     L (dir)
       Disk-Validator                   FastFileSystem
------------------------------------------------------------

The Startup-Sequence looks something like this:

------------------------------------------------------------
version >nil: exec.library 36
if warn
; running under kickstart 1.3
   mount dh0:
else
; KS 2.0
   version scsi.device
endif

;dh0: is available!
;assign sys: and everything to it,
;or whatever...
------------------------------------------------------------

For kickstart 2.0 it is enough to just open the scsi.device,
the version-command does this. For kickstart 1.2/1.3, dh0:
must be started with the mount-command. In the MountList
file in Devs, I have an entry which looks like this:

------------------------------------------------------------
DH0:
  FileSystem     = l:fastfilesystem
  Device         = scsi.device
  Unit           = 0
  Surfaces       = 4
  BlocksPerTrack = 38
  LowCyl         = 1
  HighCyl        = 822
  GlobVec        = -1
  DosType        = 0x444F5301
#
------------------------------------------------------------

The values for Surfaces, BlockPerTrack, LowCyl and HighCyl
should be easy to find in some program. If your HD is
formated with the old file system, I think removing the
FileSystem and DosType fields is a good idea. Maybe it is
more likely it is formated with file systems that came after
FFS, but I don't know if it is possible to get it running
under kickstart 1.2/1.3 then.


@endnode
@node History

5. History
¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
1.0 (4.6.96)
· First release.

1.1 (21.5.97)
· scsi.device calls expansion.library/AddBootNode(), which
  is a V36+ function. So I patch that call to a function
  that first checks the version of expansion.library. In
  release 1.0 that patch was not properly done.
  

